The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, March 18, 2004 				 General Motors R amp;D centre in Bangalore
																								New Delhi, March 17 (PTI): General Motors, the worlds largest carmaker, has said it would set up a research and development centre in Bangalore, the first outside the US, with an investment of $21 million.																								General Motors India (GMI) president and managing director Aditya Vij said the proposed centre would employ 400 engineers.																								We will design the engineering centre in India, which will ultimately support our auto manufacturing presence not only in the country but also in the Asian region, he said.																								The move assumes significance in the wake of GMIs proposed acquisition of the car assembly unit of beleaguered Daewoo Motors India. 																								The Indian arm of GM also aims to break even in 2004 on an investment of Rs 1,200 crore. 
